Crimea and Sudetenland, a similar case ?
BRUSSELS – Russia's takeover of Crimea constitutes the most egregious example of aggression in peacetime that Europe has known since Nazi Germany annexed the Sudetenland in 1938.
It is certainly customary today to downplay the importance of the "lessons of Munich" when bringing up this episode, which saw Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier give in to Hitler's demands on Czechoslovakia in order to appease the Führer.
However, if the Western world were to turn a blind eye to the annexation of Crimea – the second case of an invasion of a sovereign territory by Russian President Vladimir Putin, after the 2008 takeover of Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia – the current democratic leaders might deeply regret their inaction.
In the Western capitals, reactions have so far been mixed.
The sanctions currently being considered – expulsion from the G8, for instance – would seem amusing if the threat to peace in Europe were not so serious.
Poutine considers the collapse of the Soviet Union as the most severe calamity of the modern era, the man tirelessly endeavouring to resurrect a fallen Russian empire.
If the West wants to be taken seriously, it will have to act with the same determination that Putin shows.
The numerous successes of the Russian president within the framework of his imperial project have cost him almost nothing so far.
His initiative in favor of an Eurasian Economic Community allowed Russia to win over a number of energy-rich states, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
Georgia was dissected in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, the Russian intimidation has pushed it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And here is the most precious geostrategic trophy that exists – Ukraine – which might well fall into Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia "stops being an empire," as explained by former US national security adviser Zbigniew Brzezinski; "on the other hand, with a Ukraine that has been corrupted and then subordinated, Russia automatically becomes an empire again." And since the vast majority of Ukrainians have no desire to join Putin's empire, it is very likely that the Russian-led country is now a highly militarized state, a sort of Soviet Union without a communist party.
It is essential that the international community's reaction is up to the level of adventurism displayed by Putin.
Cancellation of summits, proposals for commercial agreements, and other participations in forums as unproductive as the G8 cannot suffice.
Only steps involving the imposition of tangible economic sanctions, capable of affecting Russian citizens – who, let's recall, continue to re-elect Putin to power – will allow us to hope to see the Kremlin deviate from its expansionist path.
What kind of sanctions might it be?
First, Turkey could decide to close the Dardanelles to Russian transports, as it did after the 2008 Russia-Georgia war.
At the time, Turkey had blocked access to the Black Sea to prevent America from intervening, although it now appears clearly that this was not the intention of the United States.
Today, Turkey could choose to close the Turkish straits not only to Russian warships, but also to all commercial passenger ships heading to Russian ports on the Black Sea.
The impact on Russia's economy – as well as on Putin's military claims – would prove considerable.
Turkey is permitted to close the Dardanelles under an amendment made in 1982 to the 1936 Montreux Convention.
Turkey could thus turn the motive invoked by Putin to justify the annexation of Crimea against him, namely that he would preserve the Russian ethnic groups living there, by claiming that it itself would protect its Turkish relatives of Tatar origin, who, given the mistreatment suffered at the hands of Russia, clearly wish to remain under Ukrainian rule.
This week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to make a U-turn in mid-air so as to head towards Kiev to provide support to the new interim government.
Turkish Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who like Putin is not a softie, could thus follow suit by immediately closing the Turkish straits to Russian transports – until Putin recalls the entire Crimean troops for them to return to their bases, namely those in Sevastopol or Russia.
It would be good that Turkey could count on the guarantee provided by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in the event that Russia was trying to intimidate it.
Secondly, US President Barack Obama could impose the same type of financial sanctions on Russia as he did on Iran over its nuclear program.
These sanctions have in fact significantly undermined the Iranian economy.
Similarly, denying access to the U.S. financial system to all banks doing business with Russian banks or companies would allow for an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
Russian citizens must understand that allowing Putin, whose rise to power was based on a promise to put an end to the shortages of the early post-Soviet era, to continue his aggressive imperialist actions could come at a great cost to them.
Thirdly, it would be possible for Obama to remind the Chinese of their role in Eurasian stability.
A genuine drama in Putin's eyes, the disintegration of the Soviet Union constituted for China the most formidable geostrategic windfall one can imagine.
In an instant, this empire that had ravished several million hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries, and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation, has simply and purely vaporized.
Since then, the independent states of Central Asia, and Ukraine itself, have become major commercial partners of China.
China has been seriously displeased by Russia's invasion of Georgia, as was evident at the Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit held in the aftermath of the war (this regional grouping comprised of certain ex-Soviet states sharing borders with China and the motherland).
Russia attempted to get the OSCE to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
The Organisation however expressed its disagreement.
Or, the Central Asian member countries – Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan – would never have risen up against the Kremlin without China's support.
It now falls to Chinese President Xi Jinping to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's boldness.
The true test of this Chinese claim of being a true and responsible main player among the international community will indeed be played out very soon at the United Nations.
Will China support this blatant violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it align itself in support of Ukraine's territorial integrity ?
Two other options for sanctions are also possible.
Each Russian official could thus have their visas refused or cancelled.
It would also be possible to freeze a certain number of assets, particularly those that have been laundered by oligarchs close to Putin.
It is only when pain becomes unbearable, and notably for the elite, that this kind of struggle led by Putin today will fail.
The price of inaction might well be considerable.
A number of countries, from Japan to Israel, count on this promise from America of acting with firmness against any serious threat to peace.
In addition, when Ukraine relinquished its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so on the express condition that the United States (alongside the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, no one could blame Ukraine if it decided to de-nuclearize its defense (which it remains capable of doing technologically).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him in the famous phrase 'You had a choice between war and dishonor.'
You have chosen dishonour, and you will have war. Obama and the other Western leaders are today confronted with a similar choice.
If they were to choose the path of shame, we can be sure that the audacious Putin will serve them a new war sooner or later.
